   <titleInfo>
      <title>Letter, E.A. Glass in Chattanooga, Tenn. to O.P. Temple in Knoxville, Tenn., 1861 June 16</title>
   </titleInfo>
   <abstract>In this letter, dated June 16, 1861 E.A. Glass in Chattanooga, Tenn. writes to O.P. Temple in Knoxville, Tenn., to request that Temple write to Constable William Rogers to "indulge" him on an outstanding debt. Rogers has seized some of Glass' property in repayment of the debt. Glass suggests that if Temple does not help him, he will take advantage of recent legislation that states "debts due to Northern men cannot be forced."</abstract>
